<subSubSection id="C3776556EE943BF0FF4DF907FA55FC50" pageId="453" pageNumber="454" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEE943BF0FF4DF907FAA9FD9E" blockId="453.[136,778,1737,2070]" lastBlockId="453.[810,1452,173,608]" pageId="453" pageNumber="454">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE943BF0FF4DF907FF3EF922" bold="true" box="[136,251,1737,1763]" pageId="453" pageNumber="454">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Body of female slightly depressed: consisting of cephalosome, short neck, expanded brood pouch and narrow urosome. Brood pouch formed by fused fourth and fifthpedigerous somites. Freeurosome 5-segmented but with traces of articulations. Caudal rami whip-like. Rostrum shield-like. Antennule 7-segmented. Female antenna 3-segmented, comprising coxa, allobasis and unsegmented free endopod bearing terminal claw. Male antenna forming powerful chelate grasping organ. Mandible with coxal gnathobase forming broad cutting margin; basis separate; endopod 2-segmented, separate from basis; first and second endopodal segments with 3 and 7 setae, respectively; exopod 1-segmented, armed with 5 setae. Maxillule armedwith 8 setaeon arthrite, 1 on endite and 1 on epipodite, 3 on basis, 4 on exopod and 5 on endopod. Maxilla 3-segmented; basis with claw plus 2 setae; endopod small, 1-segmented with 4 setae plus spiniform process. Maxilliped 2-segmented, armedwith 5 setae on first segment and 3 setae on second. Legs 1–4 with 3-segmented exopods and 2-segmented endopods; inner coxal seta absent in all legs; basis of leg 1 with inner distal spine. Leg 4 lacking inner seta on first exopodal segment. Armature formula for legs 1–4 as follows.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEE943BF0FC9AFC98FA55FC50" blockId="453.[810,1452,853,1560]" pageId="453" pageNumber="454">Leg 5 comprising lateral papilla bearing protopodal seta and exopodal segment armed with 2 setae distally.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3776556EE943BF0FC9AFC57FBD4FC14" pageId="453" pageNumber="454" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEE943BF0FC9AFC57FBD4FC14" blockId="453.[810,1452,853,1560]" pageId="453" pageNumber="454">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE943BF0FC9AFC57FC33FC72" bold="true" box="[863,1014,921,947]" pageId="453" pageNumber="454">
<typeStatus id="54D6887FEE943BF0FC9AFC57FC5FFC72" box="[863,922,921,947]" pageId="453" pageNumber="454">Type</typeStatus>
species
</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEE943BF0FBC2FC54FA44FC72" authority="Monniot C., 1983" authorityName="Monniot C." authorityYear="1983" box="[1031,1409,921,947]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Remex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="453" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obesus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE943BF0FBC2FC54FB62FC72" box="[1031,1191,921,947]" italics="true" pageId="453" pageNumber="454">Remex obesus</emphasis>
Monniot C., 1983
</taxonomicName>
, by original designation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3776556EE943BF0FC9AFC13FA63F9D9" pageId="453" pageNumber="454" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEE943BF0FC9AFC13FA63F9D9" blockId="453.[810,1452,853,1560]" pageId="453" pageNumber="454">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE943BF0FC9AFC13FC0EFC36" bold="true" box="[863,971,989,1015]" pageId="453" pageNumber="454">Remarks</emphasis>
. When he established 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEE943BF0FB2FFC10FCB6FBD8" authority=", Monniot (1983)" authorityName=", Monniot" authorityYear="1983" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Remex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="453" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE943BF0FB2FFC10FAF1FC36" box="[1258,1332,990,1015]" italics="true" pageId="453" pageNumber="454">Remex</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFC4B2CEE943BF0FA89FC13FCB6FBD8" author="Monniot, C." journalOrPublisher="Cahiers de Biologie Marine" pageId="453" pageNumber="454" pagination="459 - 467" part="24" refId="ref329974" refString="Monniot, C. (1983) Microra angulata n. g., n. sp. et Remex obesus n. g., n. sp., copepodes parasites d'une ascidie de Guadeloupe. Cahiers de Biologie Marine, 24, 459 - 467. https: // doi. org / 10.21411 / CBM. A. 607 E 6 AE 2" title="Microra angulata n. g., n. sp. et Remex obesus n. g., n. sp., copepodes parasites d'une ascidie de Guadeloupe" type="journal article" year="1983">Monniot (1983)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
considered that it was related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEE943BF0FACCFC31FA61FBD8" authorityName="Vanhoffen" authorityYear="1917" box="[1289,1444,1023,1049]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Lonchidiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="453" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE943BF0FACCFC31FA61FBD8" box="[1289,1444,1023,1049]" italics="true" pageId="453" pageNumber="454">Lonchidiopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. These two genera appear to form a distinct group and may be distinguished from other related genera by shared features, such as: (1) antenna sexually dimorphic, cheliform in male; (2) basis and first endopodal segment of mandible fused; (3) endopod of maxillule armedwith 5 setae; (4) maxilla with strong claw on basis and atrophied endopod; (5) maxilliped bipartite, armedwith 3 setae on distal part (or segment); (6) legs 1–3 each with 2- segmented endopod; and (7) leg 5 rudimentary. Of these, three features, the sexually dimorphic antenna, the 5 setae on the maxillulary endopod, and the bipartite maxilliped with 3 distal setae, are unusual and serve to characterise the group. 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEE943BF0FC6CFA74FC36FA12" authorityName=", Monniot" authorityYear="1983" box="[937,1011,1466,1491]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Remex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="453" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE943BF0FC6CFA74FC36FA12" box="[937,1011,1466,1491]" italics="true" pageId="453" pageNumber="454">Remex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not confusable with 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEE943BF0FACCFA77FA61FA12" authorityName="Vanhoffen" authorityYear="1917" box="[1289,1444,1465,1491]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Lonchidiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="453" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEE943BF0FACCFA77FA61FA12" box="[1289,1444,1465,1491]" italics="true" pageId="453" pageNumber="454">Lonchidiopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, because it has 3-segmented exopods in legs 1–3, and displays a peculiar form of the caudal rami and leg 4.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
